{"id":"1901.05019","submitter":"Sihan Yuan","authors":"Sihan Yuan, and Daniel J. Eisenstein","title":"Decorrelating the errors of the galaxy correlation function with compact\n  transformation matrices","comments":"17 pages, 14 figures, submitted to MNRAS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stz899","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Covariance matrix estimation is a persistent challenge for cosmology, often\nrequiring a large number of synthetic mock catalogues. The off-diagonal\ncomponents of the covariance matrix also make it difficult to show\nrepresentative error bars on the 2-point correlation function (2PCF), since\nerrors computed from the diagonal values of the covariance matrix greatly\nunderestimate the uncertainties. We develop a routine for decorrelating the\nprojected and anisotropic 2PCF with simple and scale-compact transformations on\nthe 2PCF. These transformation matrices are modeled after the Cholesky\ndecomposition and the symmetric square root of the Fisher matrix. Using mock\ncatalogues, we show that the transformed projected and anisotropic 2PCF recover\nthe same structure as the original 2PCF, while producing largely decorrelated\nerror bars. Specifically, we propose simple Cholesky based transformation\nmatrices that suppress the off-diagonal covariances on the projected 2PCF by\n~95% and that on the anisotropic 2PCF by ~87%. These transformations also serve\nas highly regularized models of the Fisher matrix, compressing the degrees of\nfreedom so that one can fit for the Fisher matrix with a much smaller number of\nmocks.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 15 Jan 2019 19:00:26 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 6 Mar 2019 00:06:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-04-10"}
